    "created_at": "2016-03-31T02:02:16Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-31T02:02:16Z",
    "body": "There are two types of event loops in Electron: one is the event loop of Chromium, the other one is an event loop that listens for libuv's events.\n\nYou can find more information about it in the following slides:\nhttps://speakerdeck.com/zcbenz/practice-on-embedding-node-dot-js-into-atom-editor\n\nThe logic of it is also easy to understand:\nhttps://github.com/atom/electron/blob/master/atom/common/node_bindings.cc#L249\n\nWe did node integration in this way so there is no need to patch either Chromium or Node, and it is efficient and avoids lots of bugs. In old times of nw.js (the node-webkit age), the node integration was implemented by replacing Chromium's event event with libuv, which was quite buggy. I don't know how it goes now.\n"
  },
